         <div>
            <entry xml:id="Lc387cbac6887448aa7fbef00a247e23e" n="12447">
               <form>
                  <foreign xml:lang="gez">ከናዚር</foreign>
               </form>
               <sense xml:lang="en" source="#traces" xml:id="Tmain">
                  <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>kanāzir</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <pos expand="Substantivum">subst.</pos>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>wild boar</quote>
                  </cit>, ‘<cit type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                     <quote>cinghiale</quote>
                  </cit>’ <foreign xml:lang="gez">ምስለ፡ አራዊተ፡ ገዳም፡ ወምስለ፡ አናብስት፡ ወአናምርት፡ ወአዝዕብት፡
                     ወግሔያት፡ ወቶራት፡ ወባቡላት፡ ወነጌያት፡ ወአሕርው፡ ወከናዚር፡ ወባቡ&lt;ላ&gt;ሰ፡ ብሂል፡ በነገረ፡ አክሱም፡ አጋዜን፡
                     ወእቱ፡ ወነጌያት፡ ብሂል፡ ሐርማዝ፡ ሐራውያ፡ ወከናዚር፡ መፍለስ፡ ወሐሰማ፡</foreign> ‘<cit type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                     <quote>in compagnia delle fiere selvatiche, con leoni, leopardi, iene, iraci,
                        gazzelle, bābulāt, nagēyā, ʾaḥrew, kanāzir: bābulā nella lingua di ʾAksum si
                        dice ʾagāzēn (antilope), nagēyāt si dice ḥarmāz (elefante), e ḥarāwyā e
                        kanāzir si dicono maflas (cinghiale) e ḥasamā (porco)</quote>
                  </cit>’ <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Bausi2003Libanos"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 119-120 § 304 (ed.)</citedRange>
                  </bibl>, <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Bausi2003LibanosTr"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 68-69 § 304 (tr.)</citedRange>
                  </bibl> (‘«<cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>bābulāt</quote>
                  </cit> ... il porco»: serie di termini etiopici con le rispettive glosse in
                  tigrino; per i tigrini <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>ʾagāzēn</quote>
                  </cit>, <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>ḥarmāz</quote>
                  </cit>, <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>maflas</quote>
                  </cit> e <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>ḥasamā</quote>
                  </cit> vd. per tutti <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Kane2000DictTgrVol2"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 1543</citedRange>
                  </bibl>, <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Kane2000DictTgrVol1"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 185, 537, 201</citedRange>
                  </bibl>; {...} <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>kanāzir</quote>
                  </cit> è l’arabo <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>ḫinzīr</quote>
                  </cit> attestato anche in tigrino (vd. <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Kane2000DictTgrVol2"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 1654</citedRange>
                  </bibl>; <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Leslau1956ArabLoanwordsTigrinya"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 210</citedRange>
                  </bibl> = <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Leslau1990ArabLoanwordsEthSem"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 200</citedRange>
                  </bibl>, che pongono però una base araba (<cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>ḫanzīr</quote>
                  </cit>), pl. <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>ḫanāzīr</quote>
                  </cit>.’ <bibl>
                     <ptr target="bm:Bausi2003LibanosTr"/>
                     <citedRange unit="page"> 68 n. 35</citedRange>
                  </bibl>); <lbl expand="videas">vid.</lbl>
                  <foreign xml:lang="gez">ሐራውያ፡</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="gez">መፍልስ፡</foreign>
                  <nd/>
               </sense>
            </entry>
